text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!The Milan Conference of 1880%0a%0a:Author: gtwei%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aA Step Backwards in Sign Language Education%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn September of 1880, the Second International Congress on Education of the Deaf was held in Milan, Italy. 164 delegates from 6 European countries and the United States met to discuss the future of Deaf education (2). At the conference, it was decided that “oral education was better than manual (sign) education” (1), and thus effectively resulted in a ban on teaching sign language in schools. The only delegates at the conference who opposed the statute were those from the United States and the United Kingdom, but they were easily outnumbered. The only deaf delegate present at the conference was James Denison of the United States (3).%0a%0aSchools instead turned to speech therapy and teaching lip-reading. This resulted in deaf teachers losing their jobs, and an overall decline in the education of people who were hard of hearing (1). Over time, there were less deaf people in professions such as politicians, writers, artists, lawyers, etc. (2).%0a%0aIt wasn’t until the late 1900s when sign language education began to return to classrooms. In 1970, William Stokoe, a linguistics professor at Gallaudet College, “declared sign language a true language” (1). Gallaudet college was also one of the few schools who chose to keep sign language on their campus. There were also more recent developments. In 2010, the 21st International Congress on the Education of the Deaf met in Vancouver, and officially removed all of the bans that were instituted by the Milan Conference (3). A formal apology was also issued.%0a%0aSign language has since become much more prevalent. But overall, the Milan Conference of 1880 had serious consequences on Deaf education. It is now viewed as a symbol of sign language oppression (2), and is a reminder as to why accessible communication is so important.%0a%0a%0a1) https://www.verywellhealth.com/deaf-history-milan-1880-1046547%0a2) https://www.handspeak.com/learn/index.php?id=238%0a3) https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_International_Congress_on_Education_of_the_Deaf%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 221209-045159-127610#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Milan Conference was a mistake %0a-> - williamh57%0a-> [-08.12.2022 - 20:51-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221209-045159-127610 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aLooking back on it, the conclusions of that conference were definitely misguided. I almost wonder if the thought-process of the attendees had something to do with Darwinism that  was also prevalent during that time period. The goal should definitely not be forcing people into a "superior" way of learning language, but by pushing them towards the best method suited towards them, so that they can contribute the most to society. It's amazing that it took almost a century for academics to realize the harm brought upon societies by the conference. %0a%0aI'm thankful that sign language is no longer oppressed in schools -- it is so interesting that besides oral and written communication we can have sign language. Sign language might even be more efficient than spoken language: https://www.britishdeafnews.co.uk/which-is-more-efficient-talking-or-signing/#:~:text=They%2520worked%2520out%2520that%2520the,while%2520Speech%2520is%2520one%2520dimensional.%0a%0aI'm interested in how tenses are conveyed in ASL. Apparently there are signs that convey some tenses such as the future tense. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221209-045159-127610#%0a#foxbegin 221209-100626-452240#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Similarities between the Milan Conference and classical Oppression %0a-> - haridesikan%0a-> [-09.12.2022 - 02:06-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221209-100626-452240 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aIn some sense, the Milan Conference was a manner of oppression not so different from so many others; it attempted to save face by "looking towards the education of deaf children" and came up with "strategies to teach the deaf via the spoken word." We see this happen in many oppressive scenarios (I shan't name examples as they are too numerous to count); the tale is spun as "helping" the oppressed out by including some blanket bullet points, but really seeks to do nothing than to advance the goal of the oppressors. Sign language, however, survived long enough to be restored to some level; much like the stories we do hear of failed attempts at oppression, there is light at the end of this story.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221209-100626-452240#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 221209-100649-360760#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-09.12.2022 - 02:06-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%